section.para:
The pipeline below uses model-free extractors and a synthetic ECB-style rate table. The dateline becomes the document date; both money spans keep their original offsets while the conversion layer restates them in USD. NumericExtractionExampleTest asserts the behavior shown here.
String text = "Berlin, 14 July 2026. The seller asked for €2.5 million, " + "but the buyer paid $2,400,000 after a week of talks.";
FxRates rates = EcbFxRates.load(ratesCsvStream); // e.g. 2026-07-13, 1.2000 USD per EUR
Document document = DocumentAnalyzer.builder() .add(new TemporalAnnotator(new CursorTemporalExtractor())) .add(new DocumentDateAnnotator()) .add(new MoneyAnnotator(new CursorMoneyExtractor())) .add(new MoneyConversionAnnotator(rates, "USD")) .build() .analyze(text);
// TEMPORALS / DOCUMENT_DATE: 14 July 2026 -> 2026-07-14 // MONEY: €2.5 million -> 2500000 EUR; $2,400,000 -> 2400000 USD // CONVERTED_MONEY: 3000000 USD and 2400000 USD on the same spans
